WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:00:20.276 --> 00:00:23.116 A:middle
&gt;&gt; IAN FISCH: Good morning, and
welcome to Accessibility on iOS,

00:00:23.386 --> 00:00:25.626 A:middle
my name is Ian Fisch
and I'm an engineer

00:00:25.626 --> 00:00:27.056 A:middle
on the Accessibility team.

00:00:28.576 --> 00:00:31.866 A:middle
So accessibility is really
about making sure all users,

00:00:32.195 --> 00:00:34.916 A:middle
regardless of abilities,
have full access to all

00:00:34.916 --> 00:00:37.516 A:middle
of our products and the great
features you put in your apps,

00:00:37.996 --> 00:00:40.726 A:middle
and that means we get to
focus on users and think

00:00:40.726 --> 00:00:43.686 A:middle
about how users with these
different abilities use

00:00:43.686 --> 00:00:44.296 A:middle
our features.

00:00:44.846 --> 00:00:47.636 A:middle
That, in turn, has allowed
Apple to create great futures

00:00:47.946 --> 00:00:51.336 A:middle
to empower users, like
the girl you see here

00:00:51.336 --> 00:00:55.106 A:middle
with a switch mounted next
to her head which allows her

00:00:55.106 --> 00:00:57.646 A:middle
to control all of iOS,
with just that one button.

00:00:57.646 --> 00:01:01.016 A:middle
And that gives her the
freedom to communicate and play

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:00:57.646 --> 00:01:01.016 A:middle
And that gives her the
freedom to communicate and play

00:01:01.436 --> 00:01:02.756 A:middle
without the need for assistance.

00:01:04.226 --> 00:01:07.366 A:middle
And as users get older
and older, more and more

00:01:07.366 --> 00:01:09.696 A:middle
of them will be using these
accessibility features,

00:01:09.696 --> 00:01:12.116 A:middle
so the time is really
now to start thinking

00:01:12.116 --> 00:01:15.306 A:middle
about accessibility in
the terms of your app.

00:01:16.336 --> 00:01:19.806 A:middle
So Apple creates these great
accessibility features,

00:01:19.806 --> 00:01:21.376 A:middle
but that's only part
of the story.

00:01:21.696 --> 00:01:24.016 A:middle
We need all of your
apps to be accessible

00:01:24.396 --> 00:01:27.146 A:middle
so we can create a great
ecosystem for accessibility

00:01:27.146 --> 00:01:28.426 A:middle
and empower these users.

00:01:29.886 --> 00:01:32.276 A:middle
Today we will be talking about
the accessibility futures

00:01:32.566 --> 00:01:33.906 A:middle
that Apple provides on iOS.

00:01:33.906 --> 00:01:39.416 A:middle
We will look at what's new
in iOS ,9 and we will go

00:01:39.416 --> 00:01:41.166 A:middle
through what we call
an accessibility audit,

00:01:41.246 --> 00:01:42.536 A:middle
where we will look at an app

00:01:42.536 --> 00:01:44.376 A:middle
and see how accessible
it is already.

00:01:45.166 --> 00:01:48.236 A:middle
Then we will go through
implementing some accessibility

00:01:48.646 --> 00:01:49.226 A:middle
in that app.

00:01:50.596 --> 00:01:52.476 A:middle
But first, let's take a look

00:01:52.476 --> 00:01:55.376 A:middle
at the accessibility
features that Apple provides.

00:01:56.136 --> 00:02:00.516 A:middle
We break those into four large
areas: hearing, learning,

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:01:56.136 --> 00:02:00.516 A:middle
We break those into four large
areas: hearing, learning,

00:02:01.386 --> 00:02:03.626 A:middle
vision, and physical and motor.

00:02:04.126 --> 00:02:06.676 A:middle
So I will go through just a few
of the features that we have,

00:02:06.676 --> 00:02:10.985 A:middle
but there are many more I don't
have time to talk about today.

00:02:11.156 --> 00:02:13.926 A:middle
For hearing, we have
made-for-iPhone hearing aids,

00:02:14.306 --> 00:02:17.296 A:middle
which allow users to stream
high-quality audio directly

00:02:17.296 --> 00:02:19.756 A:middle
from their iOS device
and control the settings

00:02:19.756 --> 00:02:20.596 A:middle
of those hearing aids.

00:02:21.146 --> 00:02:24.516 A:middle
This replaces a lot of extra
hardware the user would have

00:02:24.516 --> 00:02:25.716 A:middle
to carry with them
all of the time

00:02:26.086 --> 00:02:30.486 A:middle
and provides a much more private
experience for setting these

00:02:30.926 --> 00:02:32.246 A:middle
or changing the settings
for hearing aids.

00:02:33.756 --> 00:02:37.336 A:middle
For learning, we have guided
access, which lets teachers,

00:02:37.376 --> 00:02:41.506 A:middle
parents, and caregivers remove
distractions so users can focus

00:02:41.506 --> 00:02:42.966 A:middle
on a specific app or task.

00:02:43.956 --> 00:02:46.476 A:middle
And we even provide time limits

00:02:46.676 --> 00:02:49.656 A:middle
so you can restrict the
time allowed in a task.

00:02:50.076 --> 00:02:54.056 A:middle
For developers, we provide
an API that allows you

00:02:54.056 --> 00:02:57.506 A:middle
to provide specific
restrictions for your app.

00:02:58.876 --> 00:03:03.316 A:middle
For vision, we have
VoiceOver, which lets blind

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:02:58.876 --> 00:03:03.316 A:middle
For vision, we have
VoiceOver, which lets blind

00:03:03.316 --> 00:03:05.306 A:middle
and low-vision users
touch the screen

00:03:05.306 --> 00:03:07.346 A:middle
and have VoiceOver read
what's under their finger.

00:03:07.896 --> 00:03:11.036 A:middle
So they can use gestures
to interact

00:03:11.036 --> 00:03:14.356 A:middle
with the touchscreen even though
they can't see the screen.

00:03:16.116 --> 00:03:19.966 A:middle
We also have Zoom, which lets
users who may need things

00:03:19.966 --> 00:03:21.186 A:middle
to be just a little bit bigger

00:03:21.186 --> 00:03:25.206 A:middle
but can see the screen magnify
the interface of your app

00:03:25.426 --> 00:03:27.476 A:middle
and the operating system.

00:03:27.936 --> 00:03:31.066 A:middle
And it will even
follow text as you type

00:03:31.066 --> 00:03:32.686 A:middle
and leave the keyboard unzoomed

00:03:33.216 --> 00:03:35.476 A:middle
so you can still have full
access to the keyboard.

00:03:35.906 --> 00:03:38.106 A:middle
Finally for vision, we
have Vision Accommodations,

00:03:38.496 --> 00:03:40.086 A:middle
which adjusts the
interface for users

00:03:40.086 --> 00:03:42.966 A:middle
who might need larger
text, higher contrast,

00:03:43.386 --> 00:03:46.586 A:middle
or reduced motion so users can
more easily orient themselves

00:03:46.586 --> 00:03:47.486 A:middle
with what's on screen.

00:03:49.236 --> 00:03:51.686 A:middle
For physical and motor,
we have Switch Control,

00:03:51.686 --> 00:03:54.356 A:middle
which uses these
switches, or large buttons,

00:03:54.806 --> 00:03:56.346 A:middle
to control the operating system.

00:03:56.476 --> 00:03:59.296 A:middle
It's great for users who may
not be able to fully interact

00:03:59.296 --> 00:04:01.626 A:middle
with the touchscreen,
and it allows them

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:03:59.296 --> 00:04:01.626 A:middle
with the touchscreen,
and it allows them

00:04:01.626 --> 00:04:04.076 A:middle
to sequentially navigate
the items on screen

00:04:04.426 --> 00:04:07.386 A:middle
and perform complex
gestures and even play games.

00:04:08.216 --> 00:04:14.296 A:middle
If a user has difficulty
performing gestures

00:04:14.296 --> 00:04:16.326 A:middle
or pressing a physical
button, we have AssistiveTouch,

00:04:16.416 --> 00:04:19.375 A:middle
which provides a menu to
quickly access recorded gestures

00:04:19.935 --> 00:04:21.065 A:middle
and hardware buttons.

00:04:21.065 --> 00:04:21.726 A:middle
And this even works

00:04:21.726 --> 00:04:24.376 A:middle
with third-party assistive
devices like wheelchairs.

00:04:25.066 --> 00:04:29.256 A:middle
And brand new in iOS 9 we
have Touch Accommodations,

00:04:29.646 --> 00:04:32.196 A:middle
which helps users who may have
difficulty performing precise

00:04:32.196 --> 00:04:35.766 A:middle
gestures by changing the way the
touchscreen responds to touches,

00:04:36.866 --> 00:04:38.766 A:middle
and I would love to give
you a demo of that now.

00:04:40.336 --> 00:04:42.386 A:middle
Like all accessibility
features, you can turn

00:04:42.386 --> 00:04:45.086 A:middle
on Touch Accommodations by
going to Settings, General,

00:04:45.556 --> 00:04:48.506 A:middle
Accessibility, and you
can see the large list

00:04:48.506 --> 00:04:50.106 A:middle
of accessibility
features we provide.

00:04:50.636 --> 00:04:53.296 A:middle
But for now, we will go
into Touch Accommodations.

00:04:54.026 --> 00:04:55.416 A:middle
And you see we have
got three options.

00:04:56.006 --> 00:04:57.366 A:middle
Let's look at Hold Duration.

00:04:58.196 --> 00:05:02.936 A:middle
And this allows people
who may have tremors

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:04:58.196 --> 00:05:02.936 A:middle
And this allows people
who may have tremors

00:05:02.936 --> 00:05:06.526 A:middle
and touch the screen more than
they would like to set a timeout

00:05:06.846 --> 00:05:11.126 A:middle
so not all touches are used.

00:05:11.126 --> 00:05:14.536 A:middle
So let's turn on Hold Duration
and Touch Accommodations.

00:05:14.786 --> 00:05:17.106 A:middle
So I go back to the Home
button, you will notice

00:05:17.106 --> 00:05:20.486 A:middle
when I put my finger on the
screen I get this timer icon,

00:05:20.536 --> 00:05:23.116 A:middle
and if I lift up
before the time is up,

00:05:23.646 --> 00:05:25.266 A:middle
the touch isn't passed
to the icon.

00:05:25.646 --> 00:05:28.456 A:middle
But if I tap and hold
for the whole duration,

00:05:29.866 --> 00:05:33.076 A:middle
it will open the app.

00:05:33.196 --> 00:05:37.536 A:middle
So if I have tremors, they
won't be respected as touches.

00:05:38.376 --> 00:05:41.586 A:middle
Great! So if we go
back into Settings,

00:05:42.356 --> 00:05:48.406 A:middle
we can look at Tap Assistance,
which is great for users

00:05:48.406 --> 00:05:52.446 A:middle
who may not be able to land
on exactly the right icon

00:05:52.446 --> 00:05:53.456 A:middle
that they are looking for.

00:05:54.146 --> 00:05:56.256 A:middle
So if we go back
to the Home screen,

00:05:57.236 --> 00:06:02.306 A:middle
you can see that if I press on
Clock and then move to Calendar,

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:05:57.236 --> 00:06:02.306 A:middle
you can see that if I press on
Clock and then move to Calendar,

00:06:02.926 --> 00:06:05.956 A:middle
the touch will be passed to
Calendar instead of Clock.

00:06:06.446 --> 00:06:09.966 A:middle
So it's the final touch
location that's respected.

00:06:10.576 --> 00:06:18.256 A:middle
And that's Touch
Accommodations on iOS 9.

00:06:18.516 --> 00:06:22.256 A:middle
So, many of these accessibility
features rely on UIAccessibility

00:06:22.486 --> 00:06:25.196 A:middle
to bridge the gap between
the assistive technology

00:06:25.346 --> 00:06:26.246 A:middle
and your app.

00:06:26.916 --> 00:06:30.646 A:middle
For instance, if a VoiceOver
user taps on the screen,

00:06:31.076 --> 00:06:33.256 A:middle
it will look for the
element under their finger

00:06:33.836 --> 00:06:36.706 A:middle
and ask the element in your app
for its accessibility label.

00:06:37.276 --> 00:06:40.736 A:middle
So when you return the string
Weather, VoiceOver will speak:

00:06:40.936 --> 00:06:41.836 A:middle
&gt;&gt; VOICEOVER: Weather.

00:06:42.696 --> 00:06:46.036 A:middle
&gt;&gt; IAN FISCH: And similarly
with Switch Control,

00:06:46.036 --> 00:06:49.536 A:middle
the Switch Control user
brings up the menu on one

00:06:49.536 --> 00:06:51.406 A:middle
of your elements,
will ask that element

00:06:51.466 --> 00:06:53.626 A:middle
for its accessibility
custom actions,

00:06:54.246 --> 00:06:56.836 A:middle
and when you return the
actions -- move, pass and trade,

00:06:56.996 --> 00:06:57.916 A:middle
if it's a game app, maybe --

00:06:57.916 --> 00:07:00.246 A:middle
it will display those in
the Switch Control menu

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:06:57.916 --> 00:07:00.246 A:middle
it will display those in
the Switch Control menu

00:07:00.656 --> 00:07:03.766 A:middle
so users have fast
access to these actions

00:07:04.166 --> 00:07:05.256 A:middle
on elements in your app.

00:07:06.096 --> 00:07:09.586 A:middle
So you will notice that
UIAccessibility is really

00:07:09.586 --> 00:07:11.916 A:middle
about asking questions
of elements in your app

00:07:12.316 --> 00:07:15.226 A:middle
so the assistive technology
knows how to work with it.

00:07:16.236 --> 00:07:17.616 A:middle
So let's go through a
few of those questions.

00:07:18.286 --> 00:07:19.936 A:middle
The first one is: Do
I serve a purpose?

00:07:20.666 --> 00:07:24.336 A:middle
This is really about
whether an element is useful

00:07:24.336 --> 00:07:25.656 A:middle
or important to the user.

00:07:25.936 --> 00:07:28.196 A:middle
So a line that separates
elements

00:07:28.196 --> 00:07:29.806 A:middle
in a view is very
important visually,

00:07:30.066 --> 00:07:31.846 A:middle
but since the user
can't interact with it

00:07:31.846 --> 00:07:34.736 A:middle
and it doesn't provide
information like a UI label,

00:07:35.176 --> 00:07:36.726 A:middle
it's not really serving
a purpose.

00:07:37.926 --> 00:07:40.916 A:middle
So we answer this question
with Is Accessibility Element.

00:07:41.566 --> 00:07:45.496 A:middle
If we look at the Plus button
in Clock, it's a button,

00:07:45.496 --> 00:07:46.946 A:middle
the user can interact with it,

00:07:46.946 --> 00:07:48.986 A:middle
and so for that we
would return True.

00:07:49.536 --> 00:07:53.526 A:middle
The next most important
question is: What's my name?

00:07:53.986 --> 00:07:56.146 A:middle
We answer that with
Accessibility Label.

00:07:56.246 --> 00:07:58.976 A:middle
This is what VoiceOver
uses to read

00:07:58.976 --> 00:08:00.606 A:middle
to the user what's
under their finger.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:07:58.976 --> 00:08:00.606 A:middle
to the user what's
under their finger.

00:08:01.386 --> 00:08:05.586 A:middle
If we look at the Plus
button, you might be tempted

00:08:05.586 --> 00:08:08.386 A:middle
to set the label to something
like Button To Add A Clock,

00:08:09.026 --> 00:08:12.216 A:middle
which is a great description
of what the button will do,

00:08:12.216 --> 00:08:14.726 A:middle
but you should think of the
accessibility label more

00:08:14.726 --> 00:08:16.626 A:middle
like the title of a button,

00:08:16.626 --> 00:08:20.366 A:middle
so a better accessibility
label would just be Add.

00:08:21.276 --> 00:08:25.986 A:middle
So what's the personality
of the element in your app?

00:08:25.986 --> 00:08:29.566 A:middle
And this is really about
describing to the user

00:08:29.706 --> 00:08:32.696 A:middle
and the assistive technology
how they can interact

00:08:32.696 --> 00:08:33.275 A:middle
with an element.

00:08:33.645 --> 00:08:35.696 A:middle
So we answer that with
Accessibility Traits.

00:08:35.946 --> 00:08:38.905 A:middle
So we have a whole host
of traits that you can set

00:08:38.905 --> 00:08:42.056 A:middle
on elements that describe
how to interact with them.

00:08:42.546 --> 00:08:46.076 A:middle
So if we look at the Plus
or Add button in Clock,

00:08:46.576 --> 00:08:49.476 A:middle
we would set the trait to
Button, because it's a button,

00:08:49.476 --> 00:08:52.026 A:middle
and VoiceOver would read
it as a button to the user.

00:08:52.536 --> 00:08:56.306 A:middle
Next question is:
What's my value?

00:08:56.716 --> 00:08:59.666 A:middle
So if an element has a state
that changes frequently

00:08:59.666 --> 00:09:02.506 A:middle
over its life, we would
change that or update

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:08:59.666 --> 00:09:02.506 A:middle
over its life, we would
change that or update

00:09:02.506 --> 00:09:04.636 A:middle
that with Accessibility Value.

00:09:05.486 --> 00:09:07.926 A:middle
So if this time we look
at the Clock element,

00:09:08.426 --> 00:09:10.186 A:middle
the value that changes
would be the time,

00:09:10.746 --> 00:09:15.156 A:middle
and so we would return the
string 11:20 a.m. and update

00:09:15.156 --> 00:09:16.626 A:middle
that accordingly as
the time changes.

00:09:17.286 --> 00:09:21.936 A:middle
So the next question is: How
should people interact with me?

00:09:21.936 --> 00:09:26.496 A:middle
If the traits aren't enough
to describe how to interact

00:09:26.496 --> 00:09:28.306 A:middle
with an element, where you
need just a little bit more

00:09:28.306 --> 00:09:31.466 A:middle
information, you can provide
that with Accessibility Hint.

00:09:32.636 --> 00:09:35.306 A:middle
So if we look at the
grabber in World Clock,

00:09:35.846 --> 00:09:37.946 A:middle
we could set the hint to
something like, drag up

00:09:37.946 --> 00:09:39.136 A:middle
or down to change the order.

00:09:39.766 --> 00:09:41.406 A:middle
And this is, this describes

00:09:41.406 --> 00:09:43.326 A:middle
to the user exactly how
they can interact with it,

00:09:43.606 --> 00:09:47.706 A:middle
just a short description
of how to use it.

00:09:47.986 --> 00:09:49.396 A:middle
And finally: Where am I?

00:09:49.896 --> 00:09:51.556 A:middle
You may have noticed
that Switch Control

00:09:51.786 --> 00:09:54.866 A:middle
and VoiceOver have cursors
that move around the screen.

00:09:55.516 --> 00:09:57.476 A:middle
So we need to know where
to display that cursor.

00:09:58.036 --> 00:10:00.026 A:middle
So we answer that with
Accessibility Frame.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:09:58.036 --> 00:10:00.026 A:middle
So we answer that with
Accessibility Frame.

00:10:01.116 --> 00:10:03.766 A:middle
And that's how we draw the
beautiful cursor we see here.

00:10:04.756 --> 00:10:07.356 A:middle
It's important to
remember that the frame is

00:10:07.356 --> 00:10:09.696 A:middle
in screen coordinates, so
we provide a helper method

00:10:09.696 --> 00:10:11.536 A:middle
to convert from view
to screen coordinates.

00:10:12.556 --> 00:10:16.106 A:middle
Most of the time we assume this
to just be the frame of a view,

00:10:16.516 --> 00:10:18.846 A:middle
so you won't need to touch
this unless you need it

00:10:18.846 --> 00:10:20.776 A:middle
to be something a
little bit more specific.

00:10:21.436 --> 00:10:24.526 A:middle
And that's it!

00:10:24.876 --> 00:10:28.756 A:middle
Those six methods make up the
basic API for UI accessibility,

00:10:29.126 --> 00:10:31.646 A:middle
and that's enough to get
most of accessibility done,

00:10:32.126 --> 00:10:34.926 A:middle
so just a few lines of
code and a few minutes

00:10:35.126 --> 00:10:36.706 A:middle
to make your app
really accessible.

00:10:37.196 --> 00:10:41.536 A:middle
But the really great news
is we do most of the work.

00:10:41.766 --> 00:10:44.716 A:middle
So if you use standard
controls in UIKit,

00:10:45.146 --> 00:10:46.476 A:middle
most of this is done for you.

00:10:47.056 --> 00:10:48.656 A:middle
If you do custom drawing,

00:10:48.996 --> 00:10:50.976 A:middle
we need you to answer
these questions for us

00:10:51.206 --> 00:10:54.456 A:middle
so accessibility users can know
how to interact with your app.

00:10:54.456 --> 00:10:57.136 A:middle
So just that really
small investment

00:10:57.446 --> 00:11:00.266 A:middle
of those six methods will
give you a large reward

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:10:57.446 --> 00:11:00.266 A:middle
of those six methods will
give you a large reward

00:11:00.266 --> 00:11:02.286 A:middle
of a lot more people being
able to use your app.

00:11:03.086 --> 00:11:06.776 A:middle
So it's not that much to
make something accessible.

00:11:07.386 --> 00:11:11.586 A:middle
So now your convinced:
accessibility, just six methods,

00:11:11.866 --> 00:11:13.886 A:middle
that's easy, how do I do it?

00:11:14.566 --> 00:11:16.706 A:middle
The first step is
design for accessibility.

00:11:17.116 --> 00:11:19.956 A:middle
So when you are thinking
about your app and thinking

00:11:19.956 --> 00:11:22.796 A:middle
about how users will use
the app you are building,

00:11:22.906 --> 00:11:24.866 A:middle
think about Switch
Control and VoiceOver users

00:11:25.326 --> 00:11:27.346 A:middle
and how they will
interact with your app.

